Nepal's Chitwan National Park, accredited as Conservation Assured Tiger
Standards, boasts of having 120 royal Bengal tigers. Image by Nabin Baral.
Copyright Demotix. (26/10/2009)

Nepal's [Chitwan National
Park](http://www.chitwannationalpark.gov.np/index.php/background) has beaten
out all other tiger sanctuaries in the world to be
[become](http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=91747)
the first to be accredited by the new [Conservation Assured Tiger Standards
(CA|TS)](http://www.conservationassured.org/cats_wp/about-cats-tiger-
protection/).

Located in the subtropical inner Terai lowlands of south-central Nepal, the
park earned the accreditation from the [Tigers Alive Initiative
(TAI)](https://www.facebook.com/stripesandstride/posts/675761852488164) of the
World Wildlife Fund (WWF). To qualify, tiger conservation areas must meet a
set of 17 standards. Chitwan National Park met them all, and is considered a
[well-managed, protected and effective refuge for
tigers](http://www.nepalitimes.com/blogs/thebrief/2015/02/06/chitwan-best-
tiger-habitat/).

