When a rhino is poached, the poachers hack off the horn and sometimes the
hooves, but leave behind the body. However, the case of a tiger is different.
Each and every part of the carcass is traded. The poachers don’t leave even a
single trace of the hunt – be it skin, toes, nail, bones or meat – and
everything is sold at high prices.

While the whole nation and the conservationists are overjoyed with the feat
achieved by Nepal, the concerned authorities should leave no room for
complacency. In May 2014, the Chitwan National Park officials and Nepal army
personnel [found a dead de-horned
rhino](http://www.ekantipur.com/2014/05/04/national/rhino-killed-in-chitwan-
sanctuary/389114.html ) only few weeks after the Nepal celebrated the second
consecutive Zero Poaching Year.

Even though Nepal police was successful in bringing the most notorious rhino
poacher, [Raj Kumar
Praja](http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=91840
), suspected of killing over 30 rhinos, from Malaysia, petty [smugglers and
traders](http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-indian-origin-man-arrested-in-
nepal-with-tiger-bones-and-pistols-2054234 ) are still carrying on with the
lucrative illegal trade.

The bright side is that Nepal's zero poaching has inspired the tiger range
countries Bhutan, Russia, Bangladesh, Myanmar, India and Vietnam attending the
[Symposium on Towards Zero Poaching in Asia](https://www.thedodo.com/nepal-
poaching-asia-summit-972995657.html?xrs=MARevealed_googleplus   ) to join the
effort to save the magnificent creature from poaching.

[TRAFFIC](http://www.traffic.org/overview/), the wildlife trade monitoring
network, tweeted:

> [#NEPAL](https://twitter.com/hashtag/NEPAL?src=hash) Zero Poaching Symposium
> ends with accord on 5 key ways to tackle poaching <http://t.co/hu8eSQ55Sv>
> [pic.twitter.com/7l7ZBZVz8R](http://t.co/7l7ZBZVz8R)
>
> — TRAFFIC (@TRAFFIC_WLTrade) [February 6,
> 2015](https://twitter.com/TRAFFIC_WLTrade/status/563693935558930432)

The [five recommendations](http://www.traffic.org/home/2015/2/6/asia-unites-
against-poaching.html) from the symposium, if implemented well, will lead to
zero poaching in Asia.

While the world has a lot to learn from [how Nepal got zero
poaching](http://www.worldwildlife.org/stories/how-nepal-got-to-zero-poaching?
), the CA|TS accreditation for Chitwan National Park is an inspiration to all
– to save the royal Bengal tigers and all other tiger species from extinction.

